98
00:05:52,720 --> 00:05:53,970
equation linear.

99
00:05:53,970 --> 00:05:56,870

100
00:05:56,870 --> 00:05:58,120
So this concludes part a.

101
00:05:58,120 --> 00:06:00,980

102
00:06:00,980 --> 00:06:06,480
So for part b, we're given a
differential equation y dot

103
00:06:06,480 --> 00:06:11,720
plus y squared is
equal to q of t.

104
00:06:11,720 --> 00:06:15,290
And we want to show that this
equation doesn't satisfy the

105
00:06:15,290 --> 00:06:17,360
superposition principle.

106
00:06:17,360 --> 00:06:22,030
Now, you might note that this
equation is not linear.

107
00:06:22,030 --> 00:06:25,150
And second of all, we know that
linear equations satisfy

108
00:06:25,150 --> 00:06:26,400
the superposition principle.

109
00:06:26,400 --> 00:06:29,210

110
00:06:29,210 --> 00:06:33,840
So we need to exploit the fact
that it's a nonlinear equation

111
00:06:33,840 --> 00:06:37,410
to make it fail the
superposition principle.

112
00:06:37,410 --> 00:06:41,050
And just as an example, what we
can do is I can just pick a

113
00:06:41,050 --> 00:06:47,980
couple right-hand side's q
as examples of this ODE.

114
00:06:47,980 --> 00:06:51,790
So we can imagine we have a
solution y1 which solves the

115
00:06:51,790 --> 00:06:57,060
ODE y 1 dot plus y1
squared equals--

116
00:06:57,060 --> 00:07:00,610
I'm just going to say 1 on
the right-hand side.

117
00:07:00,610 --> 00:07:06,050
And I can also take another
function y2, which say

118
00:07:06,050 --> 00:07:09,500
satisfies this differential
equation, say t.

119
00:07:09,500 --> 00:07:12,120
So all I've done is I've just
picked one q1 on the

120
00:07:12,120 --> 00:07:14,860
right-hand side and another
function q2.

121
00:07:14,860 --> 00:07:18,760
And I imagined that I have a
solution y1 which satisfies

122
00:07:18,760 --> 00:07:22,190
this differential equation and
y2 which satisfies this

123
00:07:22,190 --> 00:07:24,670
differential equation.

124
00:07:24,670 --> 00:07:28,680
So what does the superposition
principle say?

125
00:07:28,680 --> 00:07:40,020
Well, superposition says that if
y1 solves this equation and

126
00:07:40,020 --> 00:07:48,150
y2 solves this equation, then
the function y equals y1 plus

127
00:07:48,150 --> 00:08:00,010
y2 must solve the equation y dot
plus y squared equals the

128
00:08:00,010 --> 00:08:04,400
sum of the right-hand
side, 1 plus t.

129
00:08:04,400 --> 00:08:10,370
So if we try and substitute in
y1 plus y2 into this equation,

130
00:08:10,370 --> 00:08:12,520
we're going to come to
a contradiction.

131
00:08:12,520 --> 00:08:14,160
So let's do that now.

132
00:08:14,160 --> 00:08:21,960
So we take d by dt of y1 plus
y2, and I'm going to add it to

133
00:08:21,960 --> 00:08:25,200
y1 plus y2 quantity squared.

134
00:08:25,200 --> 00:08:29,490

135
00:08:29,490 --> 00:08:31,620
And now what I can do is I
can just simplify this.

136
00:08:31,620 --> 00:08:36,630
So I get y1 dot plus y2 dot.

137
00:08:36,630 --> 00:08:39,350
And I can expand out
this square.

138
00:08:39,350 --> 00:08:48,880
So I get y1 squared plus y2
squared plus 2 y1 y2.

139
00:08:48,880 --> 00:08:51,550
And now what I'm going to do
is I'm going to combine the

140
00:08:51,550 --> 00:08:56,550
term y1 with y1 squared.

141
00:08:56,550 --> 00:09:01,490
And by construction, y1 dot plus
y1 squared is equal to 1,

142
00:09:01,490 --> 00:09:03,480
because I assumed that
it satisfied this

143
00:09:03,480 --> 00:09:06,020
differential equation.

144
00:09:06,020 --> 00:09:11,940
And then in addition by
construction, y2 dot plus y2

145
00:09:11,940 --> 00:09:16,600
squared satisfies the right-hand
side of the second

146
00:09:16,600 --> 00:09:18,340
equation with t.

147
00:09:18,340 --> 00:09:21,160

148
00:09:21,160 --> 00:09:27,390
So I get 1 plus t, but I'm
left over with this other

149
00:09:27,390 --> 00:09:30,040
piece 2 y1 y2.

150
00:09:30,040 --> 00:09:33,120

151
00:09:33,120 --> 00:09:36,600
So in general, if I take a
function which solves this

152
00:09:36,600 --> 00:09:39,100
differential equation and
another function which solves

153
00:09:39,100 --> 00:09:42,810
this differential equation, and
I add them together, and

154
00:09:42,810 --> 00:09:45,620
plug it into the left-hand
side of this differential

155
00:09:45,620 --> 00:09:49,910
equation, I get something which
is 1 plus t plus some

156
00:09:49,910 --> 00:09:51,750
other stuff.

157
00:09:51,750 --> 00:09:58,680
And if it did satisfy the
principle of superposition, it

158
00:09:58,680 --> 00:10:01,710
must equal 1 plus t.

159
00:10:01,710 --> 00:10:03,460
So we arrive at a contradiction
because it

160
00:10:03,460 --> 00:10:05,830
doesn't equal 1 plus t.

161
00:10:05,830 --> 00:10:11,460
In fact, it fails to equal 1
plus t by this term 2 y1 y2.

162
00:10:11,460 --> 00:10:14,200
And this term comes directly
from the fact that we had a

163
00:10:14,200 --> 00:10:17,460
nonlinearity in the equation.

164
00:10:17,460 --> 00:10:20,450
So this is just one illustration
of the fact that

165
00:10:20,450 --> 00:10:24,020
a nonlinear equation doesn't
necessarily satisfy the

166
00:10:24,020 --> 00:10:25,270
superposition principle.

167
00:10:25,270 --> 00:10:27,730
Whereas, every linear equation
satisfies the

168
00:10:27,730 --> 00:10:29,130
superposition principle.

169
00:10:29,130 --> 00:10:32,210
This is one reason we love
linear equations and we study

170
00:10:32,210 --> 00:10:34,760
them extensively.

171
